chaconne French Spanish chacona Italian ciaccona pronounced earlier English chacony type musical composition popular the baroque era when was much used vehicle for variation repeated short harmonic progression often involving fairly short repetitive bassline ground bass which offered compositional outline for variation decoration figuration and melodic invention this closely resembles the passacaglia The ground bass there one may typically descend stepwise from the tonic the dominant pitch the scale the harmonies given the upper parts may emphasize the circle fifths derivative pattern thereof Though originally emerged during the late sixteenth century Spanish culture having reputedly been introduced from the New World quick dancesong characterized suggestive movements and mocking texts the early eighteenth century the chaconne had evolved into slow triple meter instrumental form Alex Ross describes the origins the chacona actually having been sexily swirling dance that appeared South America the end the sixteenth century and quickly spread Europe The dance became popular both the elite courts and the general population sarao chacona one the earliest known examples chacona written down Spanish musician Juan Aras The 1911 Encyclopdia Britannica claims the chaconne was slow dance introduced into Spain the Moorsclarification needed Outstanding examples early baroque chaconnes are Monteverdis Zefiro torna and steh Gott auf Heinrich Schtz One the best known and most masterful and expressive examples the chaconne the final movement from the Violin Partita minor Johann Sebastian Bach This 256measure chaconne takes plaintive fourbar phrase through continuous kaleidoscope musical expression both major and minor modes After the Baroque period the chaconne fell into decline during the 19th century though the Variations minor Beethoven suggest its continuing influence However the form saw very substantial revival during the 20th century with more than two dozen composers contributing examples see below The chaconne has been understood some nineteenth and early twentiethcentury theoristsin rather arbitrary wayto set variations harmonic progression opposed set variations melodic bass pattern which likewise artificially assigned the term passacaglia while other theorists the same period make the distinction the other way around actual usage music history the term chaconne has not been clearly distinguished from passacaglia regards the way the given piece music constructed and modern attempts arrive clear distinction are arbitrary and historically unfounded fact the two genres were sometimes combined single composition the Cento partite sopra passacagli from Toccate dintavolatura cimbalo organo partite diverse arie 1637 Girolamo Frescobaldi and the first suite Les Nations 1726 well the Pices Violes 1728 Franois Couperin Frescobaldi who was probably the first composer treat the chaconne and passacaglia comparatively usually but not always sets the former major key with two compound triplebeat groups per variation giving his chaconne more propulsive forward motion than his passacaglia which usually has four simple triplebeat groups per variation Both are usually triple meter begin the second beat the bar and have theme four measures close multiple thereof more recent times the chaconne like the passacaglia need not time see for instance Francesco Tristano Schlims ChaconneGround Bass where every section built sevenbeats patterns 